00:00:22.810 --> 00:00:24.590
Fibonacci numbers are
famous numbers in

00:00:24.590 --> 00:00:25.390
mathematics, though.

00:00:25.390 --> 00:00:26.600
You probably know of them.

00:00:26.600 --> 00:00:29.970
It starts with 1, and 1, and
then you keep adding the

00:00:29.970 --> 00:00:30.930
previous two.

00:00:30.930 --> 00:00:33.200
So 1 plus 1 is 2.

00:00:33.200 --> 00:00:37.250
Then you add the previous two
numbers, so 1 plus 2 is 3.

00:00:37.250 --> 00:00:38.340
Then you do that again.

00:00:38.340 --> 00:00:40.690
2 plus 3 is 5.

00:00:40.690 --> 00:00:44.057
Keep going, 3 plus 5 is
8, then you get 13,

00:00:44.057 --> 00:00:46.150
and 21, and so on.

00:00:46.150 --> 00:00:48.090
That's the Fibonacci sequence.

00:00:48.090 --> 00:00:50.580
So you'll find Fibonacci
numbers in nature.

00:00:50.580 --> 00:00:52.810
If you pick a flower and you
count the petals, it tends to

00:00:52.810 --> 00:00:55.470
be a Fibonacci number.

00:00:55.470 --> 00:00:57.890
That's why four-leafed
clovers are so rare.

00:00:57.890 --> 00:01:01.320
It's because 4 is not
a Fibonacci number.

00:01:01.320 --> 00:01:03.280
3 is but 4 isn't.

00:01:03.280 --> 00:01:07.680
If you look in spirals of
a pine cone, you'll find

00:01:07.680 --> 00:01:08.880
Fibonacci numbers.

00:01:08.880 --> 00:01:11.120
And what we're going to do is
this summer, we're going to

00:01:11.120 --> 00:01:13.080
try and grow some sunflowers.

00:01:13.080 --> 00:01:16.330
And in the head of the
sunflower, that's just packed

00:01:16.330 --> 00:01:18.230
full of seeds.

00:01:18.230 --> 00:01:20.340
And they'll grow in spirals.

00:01:20.340 --> 00:01:22.960
And the number of spirals,
again, tends to

00:01:22.960 --> 00:01:24.620
be a Fibonacci number.

00:01:24.620 --> 00:01:27.320
Imagine it like spokes
of a bicycle.

00:01:27.320 --> 00:01:30.960
But instead of just straight
radially coming out from the

00:01:30.960 --> 00:01:33.460
center, they'll curve,
so they're spirals.

00:01:33.460 --> 00:01:35.870
Like spokes on a bicycle, then,
you can have more than

00:01:35.870 --> 00:01:37.680
one spiral.

00:01:37.680 --> 00:01:42.700
And we expect it to be maybe 55,
that's a Fibonacci number.

00:01:42.700 --> 00:01:45.460
Maybe 89 if you've got
a large sunflower,

00:01:45.460 --> 00:01:46.670
that's a Fibonacci number.

00:01:46.670 --> 00:01:49.620
So we're doing this to celebrate
Turing year.

00:01:49.620 --> 00:01:52.300
So this year is 100
years since the

00:01:52.300 --> 00:01:53.970
birth of Alan Turing.

00:01:53.970 --> 00:01:56.870
Alan Turing is one of our
great 20th century

00:01:56.870 --> 00:01:57.880
mathematicians.

00:01:57.880 --> 00:02:01.200
He was a mathematician, a World
War II code breaker,

00:02:01.200 --> 00:02:04.990
father of computer science,
and was interested in

00:02:04.990 --> 00:02:06.520
mathematics in nature.

00:02:06.520 --> 00:02:09.900
This problem was one of the
problems he studied near the

00:02:09.900 --> 00:02:11.600
end of his life.

00:02:11.600 --> 00:02:15.390
So to celebrate the life of Alan
Turing and to brighten up

00:02:15.390 --> 00:02:18.210
Brady's garden a little bit,
